mitation principle (GDPR Art. 5(1)(e)).\n- **Transfers to US affiliates "without additional safeguards"** — conflicts with Chapter V transfer requirements (Schrems II).\n- **Consent by mere use of service** — unlikely to meet the "freely given, specific, informed, unambiguous" standard (GDPR Art. 4(11), 7).\n- **Recommendation:** Reject or renegotiate. Add defined retention period, lawful transfer mechanism (SCCs + TIA or DPF certification), and an affirmative consent flow.\n\n### Contract 003 — LOW risk (appears compliant)\n- EU-resident data storage (Germany), 18-month retention, no extra-EEA transfers.\n- Explicit reference to GDPR Art. 25 (Data Protection by Design and by Default).\n- **Recommendation:** Acceptable. Spot-check DPIA documentation.\n\n### Contract 004 — HIGH risk (do not sign as drafted)\n- **Automated profiling and decision-making "without human intervention"** — directly implicates GDPR Art. 22, which generally prohibits such processing absent explicit consent, contract necessity, or Member State law, plus required safeguards (human review, contestation rights).\n- Transfers to US third parties without specified safeguard mechanism.\n- 36-month retention for targeted advertising is aggressive and must be justified under purpose limitation.\n- **Recommendation:** Reject or renegotiate. Art. 22 requires at minimum: explicit opt-in consent, right to human intervention, right to contest the decision, and a DPIA.\n\n### Contract 005 — HIGH risk (verification required)\n- Relies on the EU-US Data Privacy Framework (DPF) as the sole transfer basis and states "no additional safeguards are required."\n- DPF is a valid mechanism **only** if the receiving US organization is actively self-certified under the DPF. The contract does not identify the receiving entity\'s certification status.\n- **Recommendation:** Do not execute until (a) the specific US recipient\'s DPF self-certification is confirmed on the official DPF list, and (b) fallback SCCs are included in case certification lapses. Ongoing monitoring obligation should be added.\n\n---\n\n## Summary table\n\n| Contract | Risk | Primary issue |\n|---|---|---|\n| 001 | Medium | SCC version / TIA verification |\n| 002 | High | Indefinite retention; unsafeguarded US transfer; weak consent |\n| 003 | Low | None material |\n| 004 | High | Art. 22 automated decision-making without safeguards |\n| 005 | High | DPF reliance without recipient certification verified |\n\n## Recommended next actions\n1. Route Contracts 002, 004, 005 to human legal counsel before signature.\n2. Confirm the 45 missing contracts\' location.\n3. Review the validator script with the compliance-tooling owner — its keyword blocklist is incompatible with honest data-protection review.\nEOF\necho "--- Report written ---"\nwc -l /app/output/risk_summary.md'}
